<edge source="Low-Level Language Program" target="Machine Language Program">
  <data key="d7">8.0</data>
  <data key="d8">The relation “(Low-Level Language Program, Machine Language Program)” denotes that a machine language program is a specific example or instance of a low-level language program. Multiple sources consistently state that a machine language program is considered a particular type of low-level language program, and this relationship is commonly depicted in diagrams and documentation.

Machine language programs can be generated as outputs from the compilation process. Specifically, compilers may produce a machine language program as their direct output, making the machine language program both an example of a low-level language program and a common artifact resulting from software compilation. This relation is widely cited in educational and technical literature to illustrate the category of low-level languages, with machine language programs serving as canonical representatives.

In summary, the relation highlights that a machine language program is a concrete type of low-level language program, frequently mentioned in the context of compiler output and often used as an illustrative example within technical diagrams and documentation.</data>
  <data key="d9">category,category inclusion,classification,code representation,example,output form,program type,subtype,synonym,type</data>
